OpenSSH 7.9p1 for OPENSTEP

This package installs the OpenSSH binaries and config files, but it does
not create host keys or the privilege-separation account automatically.

After installing the package, do the following on the OPENSTEP host.

1. Generate host keys

   /usr/local/bin/ssh-keygen -A

2. Create the privilege-separation directory

   mkdir /var
   mkdir /var/empty
   chown root /var/empty
   chmod 755 /var/empty

   /var/empty must be owned by root and must not be group- or
   world-writable.

3. Create the sshd privilege-separation group and user

   This host does not provide groupadd/useradd. Use NetInfo via niutil.
   The example below uses gid 67 and uid 67.

   niutil -create . /groups/sshd
   niutil -createprop . /groups/sshd name sshd
   niutil -createprop . /groups/sshd passwd '*'
   niutil -createprop . /groups/sshd gid 67
   niutil -createprop . /groups/sshd users sshd

   niutil -create . /users/sshd
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd name sshd
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd passwd '*'
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd uid 67
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd gid 67
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd realname 'sshd privsep'
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd home /var/empty
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd shell /bin/false
   niutil -createprop . /users/sshd _writers_passwd root

4. Verify the setup

   niutil -read . /groups/sshd
   niutil -read . /users/sshd
   /usr/local/sbin/sshd -t

5. Debug startup if needed

   /usr/local/sbin/sshd -D -ddd

6. Start sshd from inetd (/etc/inetd.conf)

   OpenSSH supports inetd mode via sshd -i.

   On this host, NetInfo is used for service lookup. Create the ssh service
   entry in NetInfo as root:

   niutil -create . /services/ssh
   niutil -createprop . /services/ssh name ssh
   niutil -createprop . /services/ssh port 22
   niutil -createprop . /services/ssh protocol tcp

   If you also want a matching flat-file entry, add this line to
   /etc/services:

   ssh        22/tcp

   Add an inetd entry like this to /etc/inetd.conf:

   ssh	stream	tcp	nowait	root	/usr/local/sbin/sshd	sshd -i

   Then, as root, make inetd reread /etc/inetd.conf by sending it SIGHUP.
   For example:

   ps auxww | grep '(inetd)'
   kill -HUP <inetd-pid>

   If inetd is not already running, start it as root with:

   /usr/etc/inetd

   In inetd mode, you will not see a permanent sshd process after boot.
   Instead, verify that inetd is listening on port 22:

   netstat -an | grep '\.22 '
